{"type":"message","id":"783313d4","parentId":"b1206486","timestamp":"2026-05-15T14:05:37.433Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Python script is failing to get the token, but the curl command works fine. Let me debug what's happening with the urllib approach vs curl.\n\nActually wait - the Python script also says it got the token (line 13 is the token extraction line). But it says KeyError. Let me check - maybe the app_secret is wrong in the script. I hardcoded it as \"sWYftqexbMf6p1fYdJxqGn9U\" but it should be read from the config.\n\nWait no - I hardcoded the secret in the script as \"sWYftqexbMf6p1fYdJxqGn9U\". But earlier when I printed it from the config, it showed \"sWYftqex...\" which matched. \n\nThe curl test succeeded and returned a token, so the credentials are definitely working. But when I use the same app_id and app_secret in the Python script, it's returning something that doesn't have the tenant_access_token key - I need to figure out what's different between the curl request and the urllib request.\n\nWait, maybe I hardcoded the wrong app_secret in the Python script. The config shows \"sWYftqex...\" but I put \"sWYftqexbMf6p1fYdJxqGn9U\" in the script - let me verify those match.\n\nActually, looking at the raw output from earlier, the response from curl was `{\"code\":0,\"expire\":4101,\"msg\":\"ok\",\"tenant_access_token\":\"t-g1045flcPHKCAZ4NTOGKE2RLYMUGSSIOZVLIJ2EZ\"}`. The token extraction part of the Python script worked fine (printing the first 20 characters worked), so the issue must be something else in how the script is handling the response.\n\nLet me trace through this more carefully - the print statement shows `Token: t-g1045flcPHKCA...` which means the token was successfully extracted. But then line 13 crashes with a KeyError. If the print on line 11 worked, then the token was definitely retrieved, so something else must be failing on line 13.\n\nOh wait - I think I see it now. Line 10 gets the token from the urllib response, line 11 prints it, and then line 13 tries to get it again but from something that's empty or structured differently. The error message shows `Token: t-g1045flcPHKCA...` which is exactly 20 characters, so line 11 is working. But then line 13 fails with a KeyError, which means the token extraction is failing on the second attempt even though it worked on the first.\n\nThis suggests there's a variable scope issue - maybe the token variable is getting overwritten or cleared between lines, or the second json.loads() call is parsing something different than the first. The token value itself looks correct, so it's not a parsing problem with the token itself, it's that whatever json.loads() is reading on line 13 doesn't have a 'tenant_access_token' key at all. and the response is actually valid JSON with a token. But then line 13 fails trying to extract it again from the same response object - that shouldn't be possible unless the response is being consumed or modified somehow. Let me trace through what's actually happening between those two lines.\n\nActually, wait - if the token extraction worked on line 10, then line 11 should also work since they're doing the exact same thing. The only way line 13 could fail is if the response structure changes between calls, which is impossible. Unless the response isn't what I think it is - maybe there's a redirect happening or the response is being cached differently. I should add explicit debugging between lines 10 and 13 to see what the actual response contains. I'm noticing a pattern in the previous attempts - the Python script always crashes at line 13 with a KeyError for 'tenant_access_token', even though line 11 prints the token successfully. This suggests the token variable might be getting overwritten or the response object is being modified between lines. Let me trace through the actual output more carefully to see what's happening at each step. I'm noticing a contradiction in the output - line 11 prints `Token: t-g1045flcPHKCA...` successfully, but then line 13 crashes with `KeyError: 'tenant_access_token'`. The only way this makes sense is if the Python script is using a different urllib request approach where the response body gets consumed on the first read, so when we try to extract the token again it's already exhausted.\n\nLet me try a different debugging approach - maybe I should test the Feishu API directly with curl first to confirm the token works, then focus on fixing the field names that contain parentheses like \"1688价格CNY\" and \"利润率(%)\" by using field IDs instead.\n\nLooking at the working fields from earlier tests: 商品名称 works (fldvzEC6hS), 月销量 works (flds43CpU3), 增长率 works (fldeLlEd68), but 售价本地货币, 1688价格CNY, 预计利润, and 利润率(%) all fail with FieldNameNotFound. I suspect the problem is with how shell quoting handles the parentheses in those field names when making the curl request.\n\nActually, I wonder if these fields are Lookup fields or formula fields rather than regular number fields. The field data shows they're marked as number type with a formatter, but if they're actually calculated fields referencing other fields, the API might reject write operations on them. Let me just test with a minimal payload to see what happens.\n\nBut before that, I should verify the field names match the JSON response exactly—particularly that 售价本地货币 is indeed the primary text field and not a separate price field. Looking at the list, I can see 文本 as primary, 单选, 日期, 附件, 商品名称, 售价本地货币, 增长率, 月销量, 利润, and 1688 link among others.\n\nWait, I'm realizing the API uses field names as strings in the JSON payload, so \"利润率(%)\" should work as a key since the API handles the JSON encoding properly. But I'm still getting FieldNameNotFound errors—maybe the fields with Chinese characters and special characters like \"1688价格CNY\" are causing issues with URL encoding somewhere in the request chain.\n\nLet me try a different approach: instead of debugging the field name encoding further, I should write a Python script that handles all the field mapping and data entry at once, using field IDs as a fallback if the names don't work. This will be more reliable than trying to debug the encoding issue incrementally.\n","thinkingSignature":"a86338e697215e291a44f7cd85ca4efa5cb18678efda6f06565e8a7f66a31eaa"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_tfg6hmu2uhxy_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\nimport subprocess, json, urllib.request, urllib.error, sys\n\nAPP_ID = \"cli_a930f78f51399bc6\"\nAPP_SECRET = \"sWYftqexbMf6p1fYdJxqGn9U\"\n\n# Get token via curl (reliable)\nresult = subprocess.run([\n    'curl', '-s', 'https://open.feishu.cn/open-apis/auth/v3/tenant_access_token/internal',\n    '-H', 'Content-Type: application/json',\n    '-d', json.dumps({\"app_id\": APP_ID, \"app_secret\": APP_SECRET})\n], capture_output=True, text=True)\nresp = json.loads(result.stdout)\nif resp.get('code') != 0:\n    print(f\"Auth failed: {resp}\")\n    sys.exit(1)\nTOKEN = resp['tenant_access_token']\nprint(f\"Token OK: {TOKEN[:15]}...\")\n\nbase_url = \"https://open.feishu.cn/open-apis/bitable/v1/apps/AKppbAeyXanToTsVl6ScxO5QnZd/tables/tblHU2do30jzinJT/records\"\n\ndef post_record(fields):\n    payload = {\"fields\": fields}\n    data = json.dumps(payload, ensure_ascii=False).encode('utf-8')\n    req = urllib.request.Request(\n        base_url, data=data,\n        headers={'Authorization': f'Bearer {TOKEN}', 'Content-Type': 'application/json; charset=utf-8'},\n        method='POST'\n    )\n    try:\n        with urllib.request.urlopen(req) as r:\n            resp = json.loads(r.read())\n            if resp.get('code') == 0:\n                return f\"✅ OK: record_id={resp['data']['record']['id']}\"\n            else:\n                return f\"❌ code={resp.get('code')} msg={resp.get('msg')}\"\n    except urllib.error.HTTPError as e:\n        return f\"❌ HTTP {e.code}: {e.read().decode()[:200]}\"\n\n# Test fields one by one with ASCII-only values\nprint(\"\\n--- Testing individual fields ---\")\ntests = [\n    (\"文本\", \"2026-05-15 测试\"),\n    (\"商品名称\", \"Lò xo cột tóc thailann 测试\"),\n    (\"月销量\", 4888),\n    (\"增长率\", -14.3),\n    (\"售价本地货币\", 59000),\n    (\"1688价格CNY\", 2.5),\n    (\"预计利润\", 16.8),\n    (\"利润率\", 28.5),\n    (\"三级类目\", \"发夹\"),\n    (\"站点\", \"VN\"),\n    (\"推荐等级\", \"A\"),\n    (\"采集状态\", \"已采集\"),\n    (\"IP风险\", \"无\"),\n    (\"行动建议\", \"正常采购首选30-50件\"),\n    (\"1688链接\", \"https://detail.1688.com/offer/123456.html\"),\n]\n\nfor fname, fvalue in tests:\n    result = post_record({\"文本\": \"2026-05-15\", \"商品名称\": f\"Test {fname}\", fname: fvalue})\n    print(f\"  {fname}: {result}\")","path":"/tmp/test_feishu2.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":126,"output":2085,"cacheRead":108416,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":110627,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778853885813,"responseId":"06565afe9220f6eacb8a4e7781ba2e69"}}
